From: rob@netcom.com (Robert Rogers)
Subject: Re: ATI memory aperture conflict handled in Linux? Not in FAQs.
Date: Sat, 4 Dec 1993 21:24:15 GMT

In article <cruden.754884080@amisk.cs.ualberta.ca> cruden@gsb010.cs.ualberta.ca (Cruden Charles E) writes:
>       I'm looking in to buying an ATI Ultra Pro with 2M, but have heard that
>the card requires a memory aperture to run correctly which causes problems when
>run on machines with over 16M of ram.  I know this can be fixed under DOS 
>(isn't messing with hardware fun?), but I was wondering if this caused any 
>problems under Linux?  
>
>Thanks in advance.
>
>
>-- 
>C.Cruden
>------
>"God help us all... we're in the hands of engineers."
>       - Ian Malcolm in the movie 'Jurassic Park'


You have a couple of misconceptions:
   *   You have to have less than 12MB of ram to use the aparture.
   *   You have to remove/desable com4.
   *   You can't fix it with hardware.
   *   The memory aparture is only a speedup - it is not required.

I have 16MB ram. I have to disable the aparture. It works fine. I have 3
16550 com ports and a couple A-B switches to get me connected to what I
want. You lose some speed without the aparture, but I live with it.

I am posting this from a 386-40 with 16MB ram, ATi GUltraPro 2MB ISA in X

Later
Rob

